Btw, the best moneymaker in COTW is to go to the Emerald Coast map in Australia, head over to the long beach that runs north/south, set up a tent on the south end right outside the mangroves, rest until 12 noon, and work your way up the beach killing saltwater crocodiles with a class 8 weapon with high penetration. The .338 Tsurugi with the 8x16 scope is great for the long-distance kills, but the crossbow and the .454 casull revolver will absolutely wreck the salties from midrange. Gold salties are worth around 1500 a piece and you'll find a ton of them

snippet.textDisplay:
The bullet drop doesn‚Äôt change when you zoom in because it‚Äôs a first focal plane scope. Regular rifle scopes are third focal plane witch will change bullet drop lengths as you zoom in or out 
 This is what Google has to say. You‚Äôll have to look up the difference in first focal plane and third focal plane. If the scope says ‚Äúffp‚Äù that means no change when zoomed if it says ‚Äútfp‚Äù or ‚Äúsfd‚Äù it will. It had to do with how many mirrors are in the scope and how they are angled 


No, the bullet drop will not change as you zoom in with a First Focal Plane (FFP) scope; the reticle and the image both scale at the same rate, so holdover points remain accurate at all magnifications. This consistency means a specific holdover mark for bullet drop will work correctly whether you are at the lowest or highest zoom setting. 
How FFP works: In an FFP scope, the reticle is located at the front of the scope, meaning it gets larger as you zoom in and smaller as you zoom out. The target you are viewing also gets larger as you zoom in.
Consistency: Because the reticle and the target grow and shrink together, the relationship between them remains constant. This means the distance measurements and holdover points you determine using the reticle are accurate at any magnification level.
Benefit: This makes FFP scopes ideal for long-range shooting, as you can hold for bullet drop at any magnification without needing to constantly recalibrate. For example, a BDC mark that is correct for a 200-yard shot will remain correct at 3x and 9x magnification.
